Introduction

What this lab is about Â· What you will learn

You are not reading this for marks. You are reading this because a future IT 481 student will open their lab at 10pm, stare at a blank topology, and have no idea where to start. This guide is for that person â€” written by someone who was that person.

Lab 06 builds a three-site enterprise network â€” HQ and two remote branches, each with a switch, router, and PC. Three technologies must work together:

  • VLANs â€” logically separate traffic at each switch
  • Router-on-a-stick â€” route VLAN traffic through one physical port using sub-interfaces
  • OSPF â€” dynamic routing so every router automatically learns routes to every other site

By the end you will have 9 devices configured, OSPF running across three WAN links, and full bidirectional pings from every PC to every other site.

Switch Configuration

VLANs Â· Access Ports Â· Trunk Ports

A VLAN divides a switch into logical segments. An access port connects to a PC and carries one VLAN only â€” the PC never knows VLANs exist. A trunk port connects to a router and carries tagged traffic for multiple VLANs at once.

On IOL/IOU switches: switchport trunk encapsulation dot1q must come BEFORE switchport mode trunk â€” if you skip it you get an encapsulation error. Packet Tracer does this automatically. IOL does not.

04

Router Configuration

Loopbacks Â· Sub-interfaces Â· WAN Links

Router-on-a-stick: one physical port handles all VLANs via sub-interfaces. The parent e0/0 has no IP â€” it just carries frames. Each sub-interface strips the VLAN tag and routes that VLAN's traffic. This is why the switch side must be a trunk.

Loopbacks are virtual interfaces â€” never connected to a cable, never go down. One per router, used as the OSPF router-id.

The parent e0/0 must have no IP address AND be brought up with no shutdown. If the parent is down, the sub-interface is also down â€” and pings to the gateway fail with no obvious reason.

R1 â€” HQ Router

R1 â€” Line-by-Line Interface Configuration
! â”€â”€ Set hostname â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€

05

OSPF Configuration

Dynamic Routing Â· Area 0 Â· All Networks

OSPF lets routers automatically share routing information. Without it, R1 has no idea 142.100.65.0/24 (Site-B) exists. With OSPF, every router learns every remote network automatically.

The network command tells OSPF which interfaces to advertise. Miss one and remote sites can't reach it. Include LAN, WAN, and loopback on every router.

The wildcard mask is the inverse of the subnet mask. /24 â†’ wildcard 0.0.0.255. /30 â†’ wildcard 0.0.0.3. Using the subnet mask instead of the wildcard is one of the most common OSPF mistakes.

R1 â€” OSPF

R1 â€” Line-by-Line OSPF Configuration
! â”€â”€ Start OSPF process 1 and set explicit router-id â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€
R1(config)#router ospf 1
R1(config-router)#router-id 1.1.1.1
! â”€â”€ LAN: /24 network, wildcard = 0.0.0.255 (inverse of 255.255.255.0) â”€â”€â”€
R1(config-router)#network 142.100.64.0 0.0.0.255 area 0
! â”€â”€ Loopback: also /24, wildcard = 0.0.0.255 â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€
R1(config-router)#network 142.1.64.0 0.0.0.255 area 0
! â”€â”€ WAN links: /30, wildcard = 0.0.0.3 (inverse of 255.255.255.252) â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€
R1(config-router)#network 10.12.1.0 0.0.0.3 area 0
R1(config-router)#network 10.13.1.0 0.0.0.3 area 0
! â”€â”€ Passive: no OSPF hellos sent toward PC â€” it is not a router â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€
R1(config-router)#passive-interface e0/0.100
R1(config-router)#end
R1#write memory
[OK]
router ospf 1Starts OSPF process 1. The number is local only â€” it does not need to match on other routers.
router-id 1.1.1.1Sets a clean, readable identifier. Always configure this explicitly.
network X 0.0.0.255Wildcard for /24. Tells OSPF to include any interface whose IP falls in this /24 range.
network X 0.0.0.3Wildcard for /30. Tells OSPF to include any interface in this /30 range.

PC Configuration

IOL Router as End Device Â· IP Â· Default Route

In this lab PCs are Cisco IOL routers acting as end devices â€” not VPCS. You configure them exactly like a router interface. The critical extra step is a default route â€” without it the PC can reach its gateway but nothing beyond.

Do NOT use VPCS syntax ip 142.100.64.11/24 142.100.64.1 on an IOL PC â€” it fails with "Invalid input detected". If your prompt shows Router> or PC1# with Cisco mode indicators, it is an IOL router.

PC1, PC2, PC3 â€” Line-by-Line Configuration

Verification & Testing

OSPF Neighbors Â· Routing Tables Â· Ping Tests

These verification commands are how you ask the network what is actually happening. Don't guess â€” run them and read carefully.

OSPF Neighbor State â€” run on every router

You want FULL â€” that means OSPF has converged and routes are being exchanged.

R1 â€” show ip ospf neighbor: both FULL
R2 â€” show ip ospf neighbor: both FULL
R3 â€” show ip ospf neighbor: both FULL
FULLOSPF has fully converged. Routes are exchanged. This is what you want.
INIT / 2WAYStill forming. Wait 30 seconds. If stuck, check your network statements.
EXSTARTUsually a subnet mask mismatch on a WAN link. Both ends of a /30 must use 255.255.255.252.
Empty outputNo neighbors at all. Check interfaces are up and network statements cover the right ranges.

Ping Tests â€” Tasks 3 & 4

Five !!!!! = 100% success. A dot . = timeout. You need all !!!!! on every test.

PC1 â€” Task 3: ping PC2, PC3, all loopbacks â€” all 5/5 âœ…
PC2 â€” Task 4: ping PC1, PC3, all loopbacks â€” all 5/5 âœ…
PC3 â€” Task 4: ping PC1, PC2, all loopbacks â€” all 5/5 âœ…

Troubleshooting

5 Real Problems I Hit Â· Exact Fixes

These are not hypothetical problems â€” these are the exact things that broke during my own lab, in the order they happened.

PROBLEM 1 Pings failing â€” PC could not reach its own gateway

PC1 could not ping 142.100.64.1 â€” same subnet, all dots, 0% success. Cause: VPCS syntax used on an IOL router. The command ip 142.100.64.11/24 142.100.64.1 returned "Invalid input detected" and nothing was actually configured.

Use interface e0/0 â†’ ip address ... â†’ no shutdown â†’ exit â†’ ip route 0.0.0.0 0.0.0.0 [gateway]. Check your prompt â€” if it looks like Cisco IOS, use IOS commands.

PROBLEM 2 SW2 trunk only allowing VLAN 100 instead of VLAN 200

PC2 could not reach its gateway. show interfaces trunk on SW2 showed "Vlans allowed: 100" â€” I typed the wrong VLAN number: switchport trunk allowed vlan 100 instead of 200.

Run show interfaces trunk on every switch and check the allowed VLAN column. Fix: switchport trunk allowed vlan 200.

PROBLEM 3 Sub-interface down even though config looked correct

E0/0.100 showed down/down despite correct encapsulation and IP. Root cause: the parent e0/0 was administratively down â€” I forgot no shutdown on it. Sub-interfaces cannot come up if the parent is down.

Always run no shutdown on parent e0/0. Check with show ip interface brief â€” the parent must show up up.

PROBLEM 4 VLAN names wrong â€” "vlan1" instead of "HQ-VLAN"

VLAN names were vlan1, vlan2, vlan3 instead of HQ-VLAN, SITE-B-VLAN, SITE-C-VLAN. The grading rubric checks exact names.

Rename: vlan 100 â†’ name HQ-VLAN. Verify with show vlan brief.

PROBLEM 5 Loopbacks unreachable from PCs even after inter-site pings worked

OSPF was FULL and inter-site pings worked, but pinging loopback IPs from PCs failed. One router was missing the loopback network statement in OSPF.

Every loopback needs its own OSPF network statement. For R1: network 142.1.64.0 0.0.0.255 area 0. Check all three routers.
09

Conclusion

What I Learned Â· One Mistake to Avoid

This lab taught me networking is not about memorising commands â€” it is about understanding what each layer depends on:

  • Trunk VLAN wrong â†’ sub-interface gets no frames â†’ gateway unreachable
  • Parent interface down â†’ sub-interface down â†’ no gateway at all
  • OSPF missing a network â†’ that route doesn't exist for remote sites
  • PC has no default route â†’ can reach gateway only, everything else fails

Always troubleshoot bottom-up: physical â†’ VLANs/trunks â†’ IP interfaces â†’ routing.

VLANs & Trunks

Verify every switch with show vlan brief and show interfaces trunk before touching the routers.

Router-on-a-Stick

Parent needs no shutdown and no IP. Sub-interface needs encapsulation dot1Q first, then the IP.

OSPF Wildcards

/24 â†’ 0.0.0.255. /30 â†’ 0.0.0.3. Wrong wildcard = wrong interfaces in OSPF.

Know Your PC Type

VPCS and IOL router PCs need completely different commands. Check the prompt first.

The one mistake to avoid: Don't start configuring without reading the full IP table. Every IP has a specific place. Understand the plan â€” the commands follow naturally.
